    85	**Invariant 4 — Engine-owned thread.** Embedder dispatch is on a
    86	dedicated thread pool owned by the engine, sized `num_cpus::get()`,
    87	configurable per engine via `Engine.open(... embedder_pool_size: N)`.
    88	Asyncio worker threads, libuv blocking pool, V8 main thread, JS
    89	worker_threads — none ever run an embedder call directly. Enforced by
    90	the bindings layer.
    91	
    92	The pool-size override exists because embedded deployments vary
    93	substantially: some colocate FathomDB with latency-sensitive app code
    94	and need to cap embedder concurrency to preserve host responsiveness,
    95	while others run bulkier local models and need to raise or lower
    96	parallelism to match actual CPU / memory pressure. This is an
    97	operator-facing throughput-vs-contention control, not a binding-only
    98	escape hatch.
    99	
   100	**Invariant 5 — Per-call timeout.** Every `embed()` call is wrapped in
   101	a timeout (default 30s; configurable). Timeout fails the call with
   102	`EmbedderError::Timeout`; does not corrupt writer state; cancels by
   103	allowing the embedder thread to finish + discard, never by aborting
   104	mid-call (no thread-cancel API in standard pthreads / Tokio joinhandle
   105	abort is best-effort).
   106	
   107	## Options considered
   108	
   109	**A — Sync trait with five invariants (chosen).** Pros: smallest
   110	contract surface; deadlock vectors closed by structural rules + tests;
   111	language-agnostic. Cons: Python/TS users with naturally-async
   112	embedders pay an `asyncio.run` / `await` cost per call; documented.
   113	
   114	**B — Async trait with `async fn embed(&self, text: &str)`.** Pros:
   115	matches modern Rust / Python / TS idiom for I/O-bound embedders. Cons:
   116	forces tokio in the engine surface (which Option A of
   117	ADR-0.6.0-async-surface.md explicitly rejected); doubles every binding's
   118	adapter; reopens GIL-vs-runtime questions. Rejected.
   119	
   120	**C — Two traits (sync + async, user picks).** Pros: flexibility. Cons:
   121	"two shapes for one verb" — same Stop-doing pattern as 0.5.x's
   122	`configure_vec(kind_or_embedder)`. Doubles tests, docs, dispatch
   123	paths. Rejected.
   124	
   125	**D — Thread-isolated impl (Python sub-interpreter per PEP 684).**
   126	Pros: real GIL isolation across embedder calls. Cons: requires CPython
